Dear Nick, Daniel &amp; Arthur (&amp; anon., if you're still reading this):<br><br>
Thanks for your comments.  Arthur's characterization of 'Nam as the &quot;gift that keeps on giving&quot; was both amusing and humbling.  I realized I had over-reacted - I'm just a little tired of folks assuming they know how vets were treated, or how we'll react, or what we think.  But maybe concerned just wanted to find out, rather than solicit a particular view.  Regardless of what concerned meant, I'll try to be a little more temperate.<br><br>
Nick, I went back and watched Apoc. Now after I responded to  anon. - I still like it though I recognize it's not reality.  It is surreal, for sure.  I don't think the director wanted to make a realistic 'Nam movie.  I think he was aiming for some statement about people and what they're capable of, using 'Nam as a vehicle.  Nevertheless, there are some moments in the movie that are, to me, distilled 'Nam.  One of those is the sampan scene.<br><br>
I did serve in a US unit, with no prolonged contact with &quot;friendlies&quot;.  That has definitely colored my perception of the SVN.  God Bless you for getting your friend and his family out.<br><br>
Happy New Year to all of you, peace, and Welcome Home.  It's good to have you back.
